\details{
The backend owns its cluster: it is created when
\code{parallel_backend()} is called and must be shut down with
\code{\link[=parallel_stop]{parallel_stop()}} when no longer needed. Each node runs at most one job
at a time, so \code{max_workers} for a stage using this backend must not
exceed the number of workers (enforced by \code{pump()}).

Passing the same backend to several \code{pump()} stages shares its cluster
between them — this is the normal way to run a multi-stage pipeline on
one worker pool. Node availability is tracked at the backend level and
results are received per node, so concurrent stages cannot cross-wire.
The one sizing rule is that the \code{max_workers} of the stages sharing the
backend must not sum to more than the number of workers; since each
stage's \code{max_workers} defaults to the full worker count, set it
explicitly on every sharing stage (e.g. a pool of \code{n + 1} workers
serving a read stage with \code{max_workers = n} and a write stage with
\code{max_workers = 1}). Oversubscribing fails at dispatch time with a
free-node invariant error. Jobs in a shared pool have no node affinity;
to isolate worker pools per stage (different hosts, retry settings, or
worker state), create a separate backend for each stage instead — see
the "Pooling strategies" section of \code{vignette("siphon")}.

This backend uses the unexported \code{sendCall()} and \code{recvResult()}
functions from the \code{parallel} package to communicate with cluster nodes.
